WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.040
How many times has this happened to you?

00:03.040 --> 00:06.940
You're watching one of those popular science programs when suddenly you're bombarded

00:06.940 --> 00:11.880
with the outlandish claim that nothing travels faster than the speed of light.

00:11.880 --> 00:15.880
It's a common expression to be sure, and physicists love to remind us of this fact

00:15.880 --> 00:20.840
at every opportunity, but how many times have those same science educators ever stop to

00:20.840 --> 00:23.960
explain why this must be the case?

00:23.960 --> 00:28.480
It's an insanely counter-intuitive thing to say, yet most educational resources seem

00:28.480 --> 00:32.820
to just treat it as a brute fact of life, as if the universe itself is just really

00:32.820 --> 00:36.160
quirky that way, so quit your whining and get used to it.

00:36.160 --> 00:40.880
Even Einstein himself seems to just postulate it outright in his original work, and all

00:40.880 --> 00:45.640
the laws of special relativity just happen to fall out of the mathematics once you do.

00:45.640 --> 00:48.840
But what if I told you that it didn't have to be that way?

00:48.840 --> 00:53.880
The universality of the speed of light is not some quirky foible we all have to live with.

00:53.880 --> 00:57.720
Rather, it's a fundamental statement about the nature of space and time.

00:57.920 --> 01:01.840
There's even a surprisingly simple proof of this fact, and it's been well-documented

01:01.840 --> 01:04.240
in the literature for many decades.

01:04.240 --> 01:09.120
Yet for some very strange reason, it never quite made its way into our textbooks.

01:09.120 --> 01:13.080
Most popular science educators are therefore blissfully unaware of it, and they can't

01:13.080 --> 01:15.720
help but spread confusing misinformation as a result.

01:15.720 --> 01:21.120
It's a real shame, too, because the proof itself is surprisingly simple and elegant.

01:21.120 --> 01:25.280
Anyone with a basic comprehension of calculus can replicate it for themselves, which means

01:25.360 --> 01:29.560
you don't need an advanced degree to understand the argument.

01:29.560 --> 01:31.280
Here's how it works.

01:31.280 --> 01:36.200
I'd like to introduce you to the intrepid space explorer, Annie the Astronaut.

01:36.200 --> 01:40.000
At this particular moment, Annie just so happens to be soaring through the furthest

01:40.000 --> 01:44.840
reaches of outer space, far away from any massive objects like stars or planets.

01:44.840 --> 01:50.400
As part of her mission mandate, Annie must catalog her encounters with any passing objects,

01:50.400 --> 01:54.880
and she naturally accomplishes her task through the use of a very large and very sophisticated

01:55.000 --> 01:56.000
meter stick.

01:56.000 --> 02:00.880
Furthermore, any time she measures the location of a passing object, she uses her on-board

02:00.880 --> 02:03.600
clock to record the time at which it occurred.

02:03.600 --> 02:10.200
The result is thus an ordered pair of numbers, x, t, which physicists refer to as an event.

02:10.200 --> 02:14.920
Now let us imagine what would happen if a second space explorer, whom we'll call Jim,

02:14.920 --> 02:17.120
just so happens to cruise on by.

02:17.120 --> 02:21.160
Just like Annie, Jim is also charged with taking his own measurements, which means he

02:21.160 --> 02:25.400
also has his own space age meter stick and on-board clock.

02:25.400 --> 02:29.480
Jim, however, is moving with some velocity v relative to Annie.

02:29.480 --> 02:34.160
Using the language of physics, we would therefore say that Jim travels in his own inertial frame

02:34.160 --> 02:35.400
of reference.

02:35.400 --> 02:40.000
Unsurprisingly, Jim therefore measures his events a little bit differently, and we can

02:40.000 --> 02:44.400
represent his perspective through the coordinates x' and t'.

02:44.400 --> 02:49.040
Finally, for the sake of personal convenience, we may further assume that Jim and Annie both

02:49.040 --> 02:53.000
agree to synchronize their instruments at the moment their origins intersect, which

02:53.000 --> 02:57.360
means they both agree to label that event as 00.

02:57.360 --> 03:02.040
Now suppose that Annie and Jim both observe an event during their encounter.

03:02.040 --> 03:06.000
Say a piece of nearby space rock happens to collide with another.

03:06.000 --> 03:10.880
Naturally, Annie performs her measurement, which she records as the numbers x, t.

03:10.880 --> 03:17.000
Likewise, Jim does the same thing from his perspective, resulting in x', t'.

03:17.000 --> 03:18.500
So far so good, right?

03:18.500 --> 03:20.980
But this raises an interesting question.

03:20.980 --> 03:26.420
Given Annie's measurement of some event, x, t, plus her velocity v relative to Jim,

03:26.420 --> 03:33.100
is it possible to calculate Jim's measurement, x', t', of the same event?

03:33.100 --> 03:38.340
This kind of calculation has a name in physics, and it is called a transformation.

03:38.340 --> 03:43.300
And at first glance, it almost comes across as a boringly trivial thing to ask, doesn't

03:43.300 --> 03:44.300
it?

03:44.300 --> 03:47.980
Yet that's exactly what makes this thought experiment so beautiful.

03:47.980 --> 03:51.980
It just feels like the result ought to be intuitively dull.

03:51.980 --> 03:56.460
But let's suppose, just for the sake of argument, that we know nothing whatsoever about the

03:56.460 --> 04:00.100
underlying nature of space, time, or motion.

04:00.100 --> 04:04.980
What minimal set of assumptions do we require in order to generate a unique solution that

04:04.980 --> 04:08.100
also jives with our everyday experience?

04:08.100 --> 04:12.420
Not many people realize it, but this simple question is the foundation of Einstein's

04:12.420 --> 04:14.500
theory of special relativity.

04:14.620 --> 04:18.620
It's such a deceptively boring question, too, that most people would never even think

04:18.620 --> 04:19.620
to ask it.

04:19.620 --> 04:23.980
At the moment we take the time to walk through it, we are immediately forced to abandon every

04:23.980 --> 04:28.140
naive intuition we ever had about the nature of space and time.

04:28.140 --> 04:32.100
So by all means, get out a pen and a piece of paper and follow along.

04:32.100 --> 04:37.100
All you need is a basic understanding of high school mathematics, and you too can see for

04:37.100 --> 04:43.820
yourself why the speed of light must be a universal constant that no one can exceed.

04:44.820 --> 04:48.340
The transformation is a function of space and time.

04:48.340 --> 04:50.100
That's not so bad, right?

04:50.100 --> 04:54.060
After all, the whole point of this thought experiment is to transform from Annie's coordinates

04:54.060 --> 04:55.140
into Jim's.

04:55.140 --> 04:59.580
It also tells us that we can ignore such factors as the temperature of the meter stick and

04:59.580 --> 05:01.820
the metallic composition of the clocks.

05:01.820 --> 05:05.780
Presumably, these sorts of things can be controlled for, so they should not have any effect on

05:05.780 --> 05:07.140
the transformation anyway.

05:07.140 --> 05:12.460
It is also conceivable that space itself exhibits some kind of weird hysteresis effect, such

05:12.460 --> 05:16.420
that there are multiple possible outcomes for any given transformation.

05:16.420 --> 05:21.060
In practice, however, none of this stuff has ever been observed, so we may reasonably assume

05:21.060 --> 05:24.020
that it won't be an issue here.

05:24.020 --> 05:25.220
Assumption number two.

05:25.220 --> 05:29.820
The laws of physics are identical in all inertial frames of reference.

05:29.820 --> 05:34.940
This is known as the principle of relativity, and it is a cornerstone of our entire understanding

05:34.940 --> 05:36.860
of motion through space and time.

05:36.860 --> 05:41.540
Basically, it tells us that there is no reason to think Annie's frame of reference is fundamentally

05:41.540 --> 05:43.020
different from Jim's.

05:43.020 --> 05:47.860
Presumably, the universe does not care that Annie is 4 feet to the left of Jim or 100

05:47.860 --> 05:49.140
miles to the right.

05:49.140 --> 05:55.060
It does not care if an event occurs at 3.32 pm versus 11.54 am, nor does it distinguish

05:55.060 --> 05:59.260
between Jim's motion to the right versus Annie's motion to the left.

05:59.260 --> 06:03.940
Both observers feel as if they're the ones at rest, while the other is the one moving.

06:03.940 --> 06:08.520
One important consequence of this assumption is that any experiment performed in one frame

06:08.520 --> 06:13.120
of reference must yield the same result when performed in the other.

06:13.120 --> 06:17.760
For example, suppose Annie holds up two magnets and measures the force between them.

06:17.760 --> 06:22.580
Then for whatever reason, Jim happens to replicate that exact same experiment in his own cockpit

06:22.580 --> 06:23.920
an hour later.

06:23.920 --> 06:28.640
All other things being equal, it seems natural to expect that Jim's result should perfectly

06:28.640 --> 06:30.160
replicate Annie's.

06:30.160 --> 06:34.160
It simply shouldn't matter that Jim is 9,000 meters away or that he's moving to Annie's

06:34.160 --> 06:38.800
left at 50 meters per second or that he's doing his experiment on a Tuesday morning.

06:38.800 --> 06:43.160
The universe does not care where you are, what time it is, or what direction you happen

06:43.160 --> 06:44.160
to be moving.

06:44.160 --> 06:48.720
The magnets should behave exactly the same in all instances.

06:48.720 --> 06:51.400
Assumption number three, the law of inertia.

06:51.400 --> 06:55.720
An object in motion shall remain in motion, and it shall travel along a straight line

06:55.720 --> 06:59.160
trajectory unless acted upon by an external force.

06:59.160 --> 07:00.320
Easy, right?

07:00.320 --> 07:04.440
Now let's see what we can deduce from these basic assumptions.

07:04.440 --> 07:10.300
To begin, imagine a piece of floating space rock that happens to move past Annie's spaceship.

07:10.300 --> 07:14.920
From her point of view, she observes the rock casually floating on by with some constant

07:14.920 --> 07:17.980
velocity in accordance with the law of inertia.

07:17.980 --> 07:22.800
For convenience, let's call this velocity u sub zero just to avoid any confusion with

07:22.800 --> 07:25.480
Jim's relative velocity v.

07:25.600 --> 07:29.920
Thus, using the language of calculus, we would say that the derivative of the rock's position

07:29.920 --> 07:34.920
x with respect to time t is equal to u sub zero.

07:34.920 --> 07:38.600
Now let's consider the same encounter from Jim's perspective.

07:38.600 --> 07:42.760
According to the law of inertia, Jim also observes the same rock moving along with some

07:42.760 --> 07:44.200
constant velocity.

07:44.200 --> 07:49.400
Jim, however, is also moving with some constant velocity v relative to Annie, which means

07:49.400 --> 07:53.160
his measurement of the rock's velocity yields a different value.

07:53.160 --> 07:57.840
Thus, we have a slightly different expression for Jim, which is written as the derivative

07:57.840 --> 08:03.400
of x prime with respect to t prime is equal to u sub zero prime.

08:03.400 --> 08:07.920
Now watch what happens when we take the derivative with respect to Annie's position.

08:07.920 --> 08:13.160
According to the law of inertia, the rock's velocity u sub zero prime is a constant throughout

08:13.160 --> 08:17.320
space and time, and so the derivative naturally evaluates to zero.

08:17.320 --> 08:21.960
If we then swap the denominators and calculate the antiderivative, we quickly find that

08:21.960 --> 08:28.040
the derivative of x prime with respect to x is some unknown constant a.

08:28.040 --> 08:30.360
This result should feel perfectly intuitive.

08:30.360 --> 08:35.640
All it says is that, given some tiny change in the rock's position from Jim's perspective,

08:35.640 --> 08:39.560
Annie observes some proportional change in position from her perspective.

08:39.560 --> 08:44.040
If we then take the ratio of these two changes, we get a constant value that does not depend

08:44.040 --> 08:45.560
on space or time.

08:45.560 --> 08:50.440
If we then repeat this argument three more times, we get three more ratios for a total

08:50.440 --> 08:53.480
of four unknown constants.

08:53.480 --> 08:57.120
Now let's take the antiderivative of the first two expressions.

08:57.120 --> 09:02.920
The first case tells us that x prime is equal to a times x plus t of t, where big t of t

09:02.920 --> 09:06.520
is just some arbitrary function of Annie's time coordinate.

09:06.520 --> 09:12.400
The second case then tells us that x prime is equal to big x of x plus b times t, where

09:12.400 --> 09:16.920
big x of x is just some other arbitrary function of Annie's spatial coordinate.

09:17.080 --> 09:21.320
If we then compare these expressions side by side, it is easy to see that there is only

09:21.320 --> 09:23.400
one possible solution.

09:23.400 --> 09:27.160
X prime is equal to a times x plus b times t.

09:27.160 --> 09:31.880
Finally, we repeat the same argument with Jim's time coordinate, t prime, and we find

09:31.880 --> 09:36.640
that t prime is equal to c times x plus d times t.

09:36.640 --> 09:40.680
Looking at these two expressions side by side, we should immediately see that the transformation

09:40.680 --> 09:45.360
from Annie's frame of reference into Jim's takes on a linear structure.

09:45.360 --> 09:50.760
That is to say, it is a linear transformation expressed by a system of linear equations.

09:50.760 --> 09:53.120
And that just feels intuitive, doesn't it?

09:53.120 --> 09:56.880
Lots of things in nature are linear, so of course it should come as no surprise that

09:56.880 --> 09:59.240
our result should take on this simple structure.

09:59.240 --> 10:02.640
And since the structure is linear, we should immediately feel inclined to express this

10:02.640 --> 10:06.160
relationship using standard matrix vector notation.

10:06.160 --> 10:11.040
That is, after all, what matrix vector algebra was specifically designed to handle.

10:11.040 --> 10:15.360
By the way, if you're not familiar with matrix vector notation, then feel free to pause now

10:15.360 --> 10:16.360
and look it up.

10:16.360 --> 10:19.840
It's important to be comfortable with this stuff as we move forward.

10:19.840 --> 10:24.040
One major advantage to this formulation is that it allows us to easily calculate the

10:24.040 --> 10:28.720
inverse transformation from Jim's frame of reference back into Annie's.

10:28.720 --> 10:34.040
This is accomplished by calculating the matrix inverse, which leads to the following expression.

10:34.040 --> 10:38.520
Note that the little delta here simply represents the determinant of the matrix, which is defined

10:38.520 --> 10:42.440
as AD minus BC for a 2 by 2 matrix.

10:42.440 --> 10:48.200
All that remains for us now is to derive the four mystery coefficients within the matrix.

10:48.200 --> 10:52.440
To that end, consider what would happen if Annie measures Jim's location.

10:52.440 --> 10:58.400
Again, by the law of inertia, she has to observe a straight line trajectory satisfying x equals

10:58.400 --> 10:59.920
v times t.

10:59.920 --> 11:05.760
By definition, however, this same location also corresponds to Jim's origin at x prime

11:05.760 --> 11:07.000
equals zero.

11:07.000 --> 11:12.080
Let us therefore substitute this information directly into the transformation for x prime,

11:12.080 --> 11:17.360
such that x prime equals zero, which is equal to AVT plus BT.

11:17.360 --> 11:22.840
A little bit of algebra later, and we now find that the constant b must satisfy b equals

11:22.840 --> 11:25.400
negative a times v.

11:25.400 --> 11:29.160
Let us further imagine the exact same situation in reverse.

11:29.160 --> 11:34.280
That is to say, Jim measures Annie's position from his perspective, which he naturally observes

11:34.280 --> 11:37.840
as x prime equals negative vt prime.

11:37.840 --> 11:42.640
In other words, he sees the exact same thing that Annie did, but in the opposite direction.

11:42.640 --> 11:48.440
Again, by definition, this corresponds to Annie's origin at x equals zero, and so the

11:48.440 --> 11:53.120
transformation from Jim's frame of reference follows a similar argument.

11:53.120 --> 12:00.040
Zero is equal to 1 over delta times the quantity of negative dvt prime minus BT prime.

12:00.040 --> 12:06.320
A little bit more algebra, and we soon find that d is equal to negative b over v, which

12:06.320 --> 12:08.200
is equal to a.

12:08.200 --> 12:12.960
In other words, the two elements along the main diagonal must be the same.

12:12.960 --> 12:17.080
The transformation from Annie's frame of reference into Jim's can therefore be written

12:17.080 --> 12:18.680
as follows.

12:18.680 --> 12:24.760
Next, suppose that Annie decides to measure some arbitrary time interval with her clock.

12:24.760 --> 12:29.720
Say the time t in seconds that it takes for her heart to beat 10 times.

12:29.720 --> 12:35.120
From Jim's perspective, this event must transform to the location x equals zero, and so it

12:35.120 --> 12:40.160
appears to last a time interval of t prime equals a times t seconds.

12:40.160 --> 12:45.560
But what exactly should we expect to happen if we perform the same experiment in reverse?

12:45.560 --> 12:50.320
That is to say, Jim measures the time it takes for his heart to beat 10 times, and he also

12:50.320 --> 12:53.320
finds that it takes exactly t seconds.

12:53.320 --> 12:58.960
Meanwhile, Annie cruises on by in her spaceship, and she observes a time interval of t equals

12:58.960 --> 13:00.800
