13:00.800 --> 13:05.200
According to the principle of relativity, there is no reason for Annie's frame of reference

13:05.200 --> 13:07.840
to behave any differently from Jim's.

13:07.840 --> 13:12.760
That means Annie must observe the same time interval as Jim did when the situation was

13:12.760 --> 13:13.960
reversed.

13:13.960 --> 13:18.480
In other words, Annie's measurement t is necessarily the same as Jim's measurement

13:18.480 --> 13:19.720
t prime.

13:19.720 --> 13:25.360
This forces us to conclude a t equals a t over delta, from which it immediately follows

13:25.360 --> 13:28.480
that the determinant delta equals one.

13:28.480 --> 13:32.920
The inverse transformation from Jim's frame of reference back into Annie's can therefore

13:32.920 --> 13:35.440
be written like this.

13:35.440 --> 13:39.800
At this point, it helps to do a little bit of rearrangement on the transformation.

13:39.800 --> 13:44.000
Note that this is not imposing any assumptions, but simply cleaning up the expression so

13:44.000 --> 13:47.040
that it better matches our modern conventions.

13:47.040 --> 13:51.240
To begin, let's factor out the coefficient a, and then rename it to the Greek letter

13:51.240 --> 13:52.520
gamma.

13:52.520 --> 13:57.640
This little guy is called the Lorentz factor, and it is easily the most important parameter

13:57.640 --> 13:59.320
in all of relativity.

13:59.320 --> 14:04.800
In doing so, however, we also encounter another little factor of c divided by a.

14:04.800 --> 14:09.560
And since this is just some constant number divided by yet another constant number, it

14:09.560 --> 14:13.040
is likewise nothing more than some arbitrary constant number.

14:13.040 --> 14:17.040
Thus, for lack of anything better to call it, let us simply replace it with the letter

14:17.040 --> 14:18.040
f.

14:18.040 --> 14:21.920
Our updated transformation now looks like this.

14:21.920 --> 14:26.920
We are now ready to introduce a fourth assumption into our hypothetical universe.

14:26.920 --> 14:31.560
All coordinate transformations must form a mathematical group.

14:31.560 --> 14:35.760
For those of you unfamiliar with group theory, this may sound a little strange, but I promise

14:35.760 --> 14:38.280
it's actually perfectly sensible.

14:38.280 --> 14:44.840
In this case, all it says is that a transformation acting upon another transformation must likewise

14:44.840 --> 14:47.280
be a transformation.

14:47.280 --> 14:49.000
Here is how it works.

14:49.000 --> 14:53.160
Suppose a third observer, whom we'll call Carl, happens to pass on by.

14:53.160 --> 14:59.160
Annie therefore observes Jim, moving to the right with velocity v1, and Carl, moving along

14:59.160 --> 15:01.400
with velocity v2.

15:01.400 --> 15:05.880
If however, we were to transform to Jim's perspective, then he naturally observes things

15:05.880 --> 15:07.400
slightly differently.

15:07.400 --> 15:13.240
As expected, he sees Annie moving along with some velocity v1' and Carl moving along with

15:13.240 --> 15:16.400
some different velocity, which we'll call v2'.

15:16.400 --> 15:21.880
Finally, if we transform into Carl's perspective, then he naturally sees things differently

15:21.880 --> 15:25.920
yet again, which we can indicate using the double-primed coordinates.

15:25.920 --> 15:32.760
Carl therefore sees Annie moving along with some velocity v1' and he sees Jim moving along

15:32.760 --> 15:38.000
with some other velocity, which we'll call v2'

15:38.000 --> 15:41.200
Now let us impose the condition of a mathematical group.

15:41.200 --> 15:46.960
A transformation from Annie to Jim, followed by yet another transformation from Jim to

15:46.960 --> 15:52.440
Carl, should naturally be the same as a direct transformation from Annie to Carl.

15:52.440 --> 15:57.000
We now multiply the two matrices together, yielding a new transformation which looks

15:57.000 --> 15:58.720
like this.

15:58.720 --> 16:03.040
This thing may look complicated at first glance, but it really isn't that bad.

16:03.040 --> 16:08.400
Remember that all we care about is the simple fact that this new expression needs to obey

16:08.400 --> 16:10.600
the rules of a transformation.

16:10.600 --> 16:15.120
That includes all properties of transformations which we have already discovered thus far,

16:15.120 --> 16:20.560
which includes the condition that the two main diagonal elements must be the same.

16:20.560 --> 16:27.760
In other words, 1-f1v2' is equal to 1-f2'v1.

16:27.760 --> 16:33.280
Again we do a little bit of algebra and we quickly find that v1 over f1 is equal to

16:33.280 --> 16:36.880
v2' over f2'

16:36.880 --> 16:41.400
This may not look like much, but it's actually a very peculiar result.

16:41.560 --> 16:46.760
Remember, the relative velocities between Annie, Jim, and Carl are completely arbitrary.

16:46.760 --> 16:50.240
We're the ones in charge of this thought experiment, which means we can easily set

16:50.240 --> 16:52.480
them to any values we like.

16:52.480 --> 16:57.200
For example, I could hypothetically double the value of v1 while simultaneously leaving

16:57.200 --> 17:02.360
v2' untouched and this equality still has to hold.

17:02.360 --> 17:07.680
Yet if you look closely, the right side of this equation does not depend on v1 at all,

17:07.680 --> 17:11.760
which means it cannot possibly change no matter what values I pick.

17:11.760 --> 17:13.360
How can this be the case?

17:13.360 --> 17:18.440
The only way to reconcile this contradiction is for both ratios to evaluate to some universal

17:18.440 --> 17:22.120
constant that does not depend on either velocity.

17:22.120 --> 17:26.560
And since we have no idea what that constant is, I'm just going to assign it another random

17:26.560 --> 17:29.600
letter like, I don't know, a.

17:29.600 --> 17:37.560
We therefore have v1 over f1 is equal to v2' over f2' which is equal to a.

17:37.560 --> 17:43.800
Remember, this relationship must be true for any arbitrary coordinate transformation.

17:43.800 --> 17:51.080
Therefore, our original transformation from Annie to Jim must likewise obey the same rule.

17:51.080 --> 17:58.360
That little constant f must therefore evaluate to v over a for all coordinate transformations.

17:58.360 --> 18:02.840
That leaves us with a new transformation which looks like this.

18:02.840 --> 18:07.240
Now let's take a moment to remind ourselves of another useful fact that was already derived

18:07.240 --> 18:08.240
earlier.

18:08.240 --> 18:13.600
Namely, that the determinant of any transformation matrix must equal one no matter whose frame

18:13.600 --> 18:15.800
of reference it happens to represent.

18:15.800 --> 18:20.840
A little bit more algebra later, and we find that our mysterious Lorentz factor must evaluate

18:20.840 --> 18:22.760
to the following.

18:22.760 --> 18:27.280
We are therefore left with a coordinate transformation that finally looks like this.

18:28.040 --> 18:32.120
Clearly, the only parameter we have left to make sense out of is that little mysterious

18:32.120 --> 18:33.120
constant a.

18:33.120 --> 18:38.080
So let's take a moment to think about what exactly that thing represents.

18:38.080 --> 18:43.560
For starters, the astute observer might notice that a just so happens to have units of velocity

18:43.560 --> 18:44.560
squared.

18:44.560 --> 18:48.960
That's a little odd, but it does motivate us to rewrite a in terms of a new velocity

18:48.960 --> 18:55.200
constant which we'll call c such that a is equal to plus or minus c squared.

18:55.200 --> 19:01.000
Not exactly this magical velocity represents, we cannot yet say, but clearly there are only

19:01.000 --> 19:03.480
three possible scenarios to consider.

19:03.480 --> 19:09.160
Either a is equal to zero, thus implying c equals zero, a is positive implying that

19:09.160 --> 19:15.440
a is equal to positive c squared, or a is negative implying that a is equal to negative

19:15.440 --> 19:16.840
